WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.685 --> 00:00:02.560
HILLARY BERGH: Hello.

00:00:02.560 --> 00:00:03.730
Welcome, everyone.

00:00:03.730 --> 00:00:05.715
I'm here with Chef Carla Hall.

00:00:05.715 --> 00:00:08.290
It's very exciting
to be here with you.

00:00:08.290 --> 00:00:10.480
So, those of you
that don't know,

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:14.150
she was a finalist on the
fifth and the eighth season

00:00:14.150 --> 00:00:18.140
of "Top Chef" on
Bravo-- yes-- and is

00:00:18.140 --> 00:00:20.440
a current co-host
on "the Chew" talk

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:25.440
show on ABC, which is
a lot of fun to watch.

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:27.177
So we're here, or she's here.

00:00:27.177 --> 00:00:29.510
We're going to talk about the
new book, "Carla's Comfort

00:00:29.510 --> 00:00:30.700
Foods."

00:00:30.700 --> 00:00:33.120
Yes.

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:34.790
I'm the chef at Root Cafe.

00:00:34.790 --> 00:00:36.405
My name's Hillary Bergh, and--

00:00:36.405 --> 00:00:36.840
CARLA HALL: [APPLAUSE]

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:37.480
HILLARY BERGH: Thank you.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:38.700
CARLA HALL: I ate
there yesterday.

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:39.372
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah.

00:00:39.372 --> 00:00:40.205
It was a lot of fun.

00:00:40.205 --> 00:00:42.540
We had a little chat
over lunch, impromptu.

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:45.190
And then today, we did a
whole menu based on her book.

00:00:45.190 --> 00:00:48.380
So hopefully, some of you
were able to join for that.

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:51.760
And, if not, now you know
that next time, when there's

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:56.160
a chef on campus, I write
a menu from their book.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:58.780
You have another
book that you wrote.

00:00:58.780 --> 00:00:59.970
CARLA HALL: Uh-huh.

00:00:59.970 --> 00:01:01.050
"Cooking With Love."

00:01:01.050 --> 00:01:05.459
And it's primarily comfort
foods from the Sunday suppers

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:08.500
where I grew up in Nashville,
Tennessee, and also

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:10.570
a lot of the recipes
that I did on Top Chef--

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:13.290
the chicken pot pie, the Jimmy
Fallon-- that's in there.

00:01:18.390 --> 00:01:21.890
The Last Supper Buttered
Tarragon Peas are in this book.

00:01:21.890 --> 00:01:28.660
But the meal that I did
at Ellis Island-- that's

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:30.650
in there-- that I
really thought I

00:01:30.650 --> 00:01:32.390
should have won
because it was so good.

00:01:32.390 --> 00:01:35.160
But I didn't.

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:36.340
So that's in there.

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:41.720
The oyster stew, where I won
the car, that's in there.

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:45.100
Anything that won a prize is
in there-- or I should have won

00:01:45.100 --> 00:01:47.319
is in there.

00:01:47.319 --> 00:01:48.360
HILLARY BERGH: Very good.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:51.170
And then, you and some of the
other co-hosts on "The Chew"

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:52.520
wrote a cookbook together, too.

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:53.270
CARLA HALL: Right.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:57.360
Well, we "wrote" it,
in that we're on ABC,

00:01:57.360 --> 00:01:59.350
and we work there, and
they took our recipes

00:01:59.350 --> 00:02:00.190
and put them in that book.

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:00.940
HILLARY BERGH: OK.

00:02:00.940 --> 00:02:03.082
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:03.082 --> 00:02:05.010
CARLA HALL: (WHISPERING)
Crap, it's video.

00:02:05.010 --> 00:02:07.979
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:07.979 --> 00:02:10.312
CARLA HALL: (WHISPERING) We
don't get paid for that one.

00:02:10.312 --> 00:02:13.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:17.110
HILLARY BERGH: So
anyway, all right.

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:21.820
Well, I really liked how much
you spoke about connections

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:22.880
through food.

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:25.650
And I'm sure that you noticed,
when we ate yesterday,

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:27.940
there's a lot of communal
tables in the cafes,

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:29.610
and when you got to go around.

00:02:29.610 --> 00:02:33.260
So, can you speak a
little about how important

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:36.660
that is to not only just
be eating good food,

00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:38.164
but to make these connections?

00:02:38.164 --> 00:02:39.830
CARLA HALL: Right,
it's about community.

00:02:39.830 --> 00:02:41.820
Well, the inspiration
for this book

00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:50.170
came from the political
climate, our polarizing, very

00:02:50.170 --> 00:02:52.600
dysfunctional political climate.

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:55.950
In 2012, when I
was thinking, it's

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:59.280
so terrible that they polarize
each other's differences,

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:02.010
and it's like repelling magnets.

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:05.470
And I was thinking, how
can I show through food

00:03:05.470 --> 00:03:07.680
how we're very
similar as people?

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.290
And our differences
should be celebrated.

00:03:10.290 --> 00:03:13.120
So the spices, basically,
are the differences.

00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:14.340
And it should be celebrated.

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:17.880
So take the first
set of recipes that I

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:19.820
thought about that
would actually

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:24.160
share my thinking was
chicken and milk gravy, which

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:27.910
is basically a smothered
chicken dish in the South,

00:03:27.910 --> 00:03:31.270
like sausage and gravy, that
white gravy that you put on

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:33.382
that you hope is not
too thick that's yummy?

00:03:33.382 --> 00:03:35.090
OK, so that's the
chicken and milk gravy.

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:38.700
But if you take the milk out and
you add sour cream and paprika,

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:39.850
you could be in Hungary.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:44.440
If you take the milk out and you
add heavy cream, dijon mustard,

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:47.210
white wine, and tarragon,
you could be in France.

00:03:47.210 --> 00:03:51.170
Or if you take the milk out
and you add tomatoes, habanero

00:03:51.170 --> 00:03:53.370
peppers, and maybe
plantains or bananas,

00:03:53.370 --> 00:03:55.150
you could be in West Africa.

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:57.230
But at the end of
the day, they're

00:03:57.230 --> 00:03:59.790
all a smothered chicken dish.

00:03:59.790 --> 00:04:01.810
You're just changing the spices.

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:03.060
And they should be celebrated.

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:06.730
It shouldn't be where, well,
I eat smothered chicken

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:08.490
where I live with milk gravy.

00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:12.305
And just because you're having
it with wine and heavy cream,

00:04:12.305 --> 00:04:14.680
I don't like you, and I'm
never going to taste your food.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:16.170
I mean, how crazy is that?

00:04:16.170 --> 00:04:18.180
And so this is what
this book is about.

00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:21.103
And it's about sharing and
honoring and celebrating

00:04:21.103 --> 00:04:22.019
people and their food.

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:23.922
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah,
that's wonderful.

00:04:23.922 --> 00:04:25.630
We spoke a little bit
yesterday about how

00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:28.434
my cafe goes all around the
world in our menu, and--

00:04:28.434 --> 00:04:29.225
CARLA HALL: I know.

00:04:29.225 --> 00:04:30.410
Have you guys been there?

00:04:30.410 --> 00:04:30.910
Right?

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:33.274
I mean, I know you
work here, right.

00:04:33.274 --> 00:04:34.690
Of course you've been there.

00:04:34.690 --> 00:04:39.150
I'm just so amazed how you were
in Cambodia, and then Russia,

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:41.750
and then you were
in the Philippines.

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:42.540
It was amazing.

00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:43.474
Like, day after day.

00:04:43.474 --> 00:04:45.140
It wasn't like you've
got all this stuff

00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:46.640
and you get to turn
it over after a week.

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:47.806
That's a lot of work, y'all.

00:04:47.806 --> 00:04:48.830
That's a lot of work.

00:04:48.830 --> 00:04:49.135
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah.

00:04:49.135 --> 00:04:50.134
No, it is a lot of work.

00:04:50.134 --> 00:04:51.920
But it's interesting
for my cooks.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:53.510
They get to apply
this technique where

00:04:53.510 --> 00:04:55.650
it's the same basic
technique with just

00:04:55.650 --> 00:04:58.350
a few little moderations of
what the ingredients are.

00:04:58.350 --> 00:05:00.540
So it's really
unique, and you get

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:03.869
to learn about that in the book.

00:05:03.869 --> 00:05:05.660
CARLA HALL: So one of
the things that I do.

00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:08.284
I mean, in the book, of course,
there are all of these recipes.

00:05:08.284 --> 00:05:10.550
And in the vegetable
chapter, I will

00:05:10.550 --> 00:05:14.370
take my favorite vegetables
because it's my book.

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:18.191
So peas-- I mean, you know, I
may never get to do it again.

00:05:18.191 --> 00:05:20.732
So when you write your book,
you put your favorite vegetables

00:05:20.732 --> 00:05:22.330
in it.

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:27.570
But peas, corn,
squash, cauliflower.

00:05:27.570 --> 00:05:31.360
So I take my favorite
vegetables and I change them

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:32.130
with those spices.

00:05:32.130 --> 00:05:35.050
But let's say that
you are somebody

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:36.290
who cooks a lot at home.

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:37.320
There's a spice chart.

00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:39.710
I have the international
spice chart.

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:41.877
And in that spice chart,
you have the aromatics,

00:05:41.877 --> 00:05:43.960
which would be your fresh
ingredients like onions,

00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:45.820
garlic, peppers, all of that.

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:49.690
And then, you have
you're fresh herbs.

00:05:49.690 --> 00:05:51.900
And then, you have
your dried spices,

00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:54.280
the things that make
that cuisine unique,

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:56.500
and then whatever
miscellaneous ingredients.

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:59.200
So I have these 18
different cuisines.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:01.237
So, let's say you
make a meatloaf

00:06:01.237 --> 00:06:02.320
and you want to change it.

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:04.680
You already know how
to make meatloaf.

00:06:04.680 --> 00:06:06.686
So, now what you
do to change it up

00:06:06.686 --> 00:06:08.640
is to go to one of
those different cuisines

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:10.060
and just mix it up a little bit.

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:12.969
So now, instead of one recipe,
you have 18 different recipes.

00:06:12.969 --> 00:06:13.760
HILLARY BERGH: Mhm.

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:15.470
Yeah, the spice chart
was really cool.

00:06:15.470 --> 00:06:16.215
CARLA HALL: Yeah.

00:06:16.215 --> 00:06:18.520
Did you agree with
it or disagree?

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:19.910
HILLARY BERGH: I agreed, yeah.

00:06:19.910 --> 00:06:22.215
I wanted to add a few
more things on there.

00:06:22.215 --> 00:06:22.491
CARLA HALL: I know, I know.

00:06:22.491 --> 00:06:24.199
And let me tell you
why I didn't exactly.

00:06:24.199 --> 00:06:28.124
Did you want to add things that
were more exotic or-- right.

00:06:28.124 --> 00:06:29.540
HILLARY BERGH:
Some unique things.

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:30.831
CARLA HALL: Some unique things.

00:06:30.831 --> 00:06:32.810
And I didn't do
that specifically

00:06:32.810 --> 00:06:37.346
because when you think
about international food,

00:06:37.346 --> 00:06:39.720
you think that you have to go
to a specialty food market.

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:44.220
And I'm honestly trying to
make this so approachable to--

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:46.154
and I think about
Middle America.

00:06:46.154 --> 00:06:47.820
I just want to make
it very approachable

00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:50.490
for them, so that they're
not going to get scared.

00:06:50.490 --> 00:06:53.970
And not only are the
ingredients approachable,

00:06:53.970 --> 00:06:56.160
but the recipes
are approachable.

00:06:56.160 --> 00:06:56.900
The time.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:07:00.380
I thought about, can you make
a lot of them during the week?

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:02.217
So I steered away from
those exotic things.

00:07:02.217 --> 00:07:03.550
HILLARY BERGH: That makes sense.

00:07:03.550 --> 00:07:04.050
Yeah.

00:07:04.050 --> 00:07:07.294
And there's not a Middle Eastern
market on the corner of every--

00:07:07.294 --> 00:07:08.460
CARLA HALL: --store in Iowa.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:09.780
HILLARY BERGH: Right.

00:07:09.780 --> 00:07:10.410
Yes.

00:07:10.410 --> 00:07:12.520
So, cool.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:15.006
So I know that you were inspired
by your grandma, Thelma.

00:07:15.006 --> 00:07:16.630
You didn't get to
really cook with her,

00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:18.450
but inspired by
her, which is great.

00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:19.700
CARLA HALL: Thelma and Granny.

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:21.020
I have two grand-- Yeah.

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:22.910
My grandmothers cooked
so well, and it just

00:07:22.910 --> 00:07:24.290
leaped right over my mom.

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:25.480
You know, whoop!

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:29.120
HILLARY BERGH: Well, it happens.

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:31.080
And I had a lot of fun
growing up and cooking

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:32.429
with my grandma [? Idebel. ?]

00:07:32.429 --> 00:07:33.470
[? CARLA HALL: Idebel? ?]

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:34.636
[? HILLARY BERGH: Idebel. ?]

00:07:34.636 --> 00:07:35.789
CARLA HALL: Oh my-- cute!

00:07:35.789 --> 00:07:38.330
Freddie Mae and [? Idebel, ?]
they would've been-- oh my god.

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:39.660
Together, they are a pair.

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:41.035
HILLARY BERGH:
Best friends, yes.

00:07:41.035 --> 00:07:43.880
So how important is it to
get our youth involved,

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:46.130
and to pass down
these traditions?

00:07:46.130 --> 00:07:47.380
CARLA HALL: It's so important.

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:49.588
As a matter of fact, the
first cookbook that I wrote,

00:07:49.588 --> 00:07:51.850
I was actually thinking
about my niece.

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:54.030
Now, my sister
doesn't like to cook.

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:58.130
My niece kind of likes to cook.

00:07:58.130 --> 00:07:59.870
We weren't there
with my grandmother.

00:07:59.870 --> 00:08:02.400
I didn't start cooking
until I was about 25

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:04.680
and went to culinary
school at 30.

00:08:04.680 --> 00:08:07.351
And so then, I was trying
to backpedal and say,

00:08:07.351 --> 00:08:08.600
oh, gosh, what are you making?

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:11.520
And then, my grandma Thelma
had passed away already.

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:15.690
And then my grandmother, Granny,
Freddie Mae, she was already

00:08:15.690 --> 00:08:19.040
in her late 80s,
going into her 90s.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:21.670
By the way, my mother was still
going to Lebanon, Tennessee,

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:23.870
30 miles outside of
Nashville, to get those Sunday

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:25.720
suppers to take to
work for her lunch.

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:26.970
OK, I'm just saying.

00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:29.890
I mean, my grandmother was
still cooking for my mom at 94.

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:31.096
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah.

00:08:31.096 --> 00:08:32.470
Let's see, my
grandmother was 92,

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:34.580
and she was still cooking
every Sunday for all of us.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:35.419
CARLA HALL: Right?

00:08:35.419 --> 00:08:36.130
You know?

00:08:36.130 --> 00:08:37.559
And then you don't realize
that they were sick

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.058
until the macaroni
started slipping.

00:08:39.058 --> 00:08:41.828
And you're like,
wait, are you OK?

00:08:41.828 --> 00:08:43.280
I mean--

00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:44.300
HILLARY BERGH: This is a
little different, right?

00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:44.636
CARLA HALL: Yeah.

00:08:44.636 --> 00:08:45.135
Right.

00:08:45.135 --> 00:08:45.880
What happened?

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:47.010
You notice in the food.

00:08:47.010 --> 00:08:47.720
It's that you're
talking to them,

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:48.950
but you're really
focused on the food.

00:08:48.950 --> 00:08:49.450
OK.

00:08:49.450 --> 00:08:51.380
So anyway.

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:53.780
It's so important
for those traditions

00:08:53.780 --> 00:08:55.230
to be carried down the line.

00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:57.310
And unless the kids
are actually in there--

00:08:57.310 --> 00:09:00.880
and I think with our
food-- and even though I'm

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:02.370
talking about
international food,

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:05.780
I really like the fact
that we can keep our food

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:09.170
segregated so it's not so
homogenized and blending

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:11.030
with other cuisines.

00:09:11.030 --> 00:09:12.340
Because it's about history.

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:16.690
It's like this [? grio ?] that
you're passing on these stories

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:17.260
along.

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:18.010
And it's nice.

00:09:18.010 --> 00:09:21.860
And if they all mix,
then, for the generations

00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:25.420
that are younger than us, they
forget what Southern food is,

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:30.260
or what Indian food is, or what
all of these different cuisines

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:30.760
are.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:31.570
HILLARY BERGH: Honoring
that authenticity.

00:09:31.570 --> 00:09:32.500
CARLA HALL: Exactly.

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:33.090
Exactly.

00:09:33.090 --> 00:09:35.640
And just loving
it for what it is.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:37.060
And then you can
mix, but as long

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:39.510
as they know what
the original was.

00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:42.770
But I think, because of
shows like the Food Network

00:09:42.770 --> 00:09:46.930
and Bravo and "Chopped" and
all of these different shows,

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:49.450
kids are getting more
involved in food,

00:09:49.450 --> 00:09:51.120
and the world is
getting smaller.

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:55.445
And they're actually
putting chefs on pedestals.

00:09:55.445 --> 00:09:58.110
I don't know if that's so
great, but the great thing

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:00.770
is, they want to be cooks.

00:10:00.770 --> 00:10:02.980
And they want to
eat different foods.

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:04.750
And they're playing
with their food,

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:06.860
unlike back in the
day when they're like,

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:08.880
I will only eat a grilled
cheese and plain rice

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:10.080
and plain chicken.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:13.650
Now, I heard a kid-- I
was at a grocery store--

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:15.290
and the kid was
crying because they

00:10:15.290 --> 00:10:18.014
didn't have the
sushi that he wanted.

00:10:18.014 --> 00:10:19.802
And I wasn't even here.

00:10:19.802 --> 00:10:22.470
I mean, I could understand if
I was here on the west coast.

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:25.145
I was in-- I mean, because I'm
sure all the kids are like,

00:10:25.145 --> 00:10:27.690
ah, I don't like that
sushi, I want-- you know.

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:30.590
But I was in Maryland.

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:32.279
And I'm like, oh my
god, that's crazy.

00:10:32.279 --> 00:10:33.320
No, it was in Pittsburgh.

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:34.570
HILLARY BERGH: Oh, that's cool.

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:34.840
CARLA HALL: Right?

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:35.710
Isn't that cool?

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:36.330
HILLARY BERGH: Surprising.

00:10:36.330 --> 00:10:37.225
CARLA HALL: It was
very surprising.

00:10:37.225 --> 00:10:38.680
I'm like, kid, you cry.

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:39.970
You cry for your sushi!

00:10:39.970 --> 00:10:40.665
HILLARY BERGH: That's right.

00:10:40.665 --> 00:10:41.561
CARLA HALL: You know.

00:10:41.561 --> 00:10:42.060
Right?

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:42.893
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah.

00:10:42.893 --> 00:10:45.830
There's a child care center.

00:10:45.830 --> 00:10:48.360
Not here on campus, but
there's four of them

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.390
that the Googlers can
send their kids to.

00:10:50.390 --> 00:10:55.160
And the chef there has
told me many stories where

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:56.910
the parents have
called her and said,

00:10:56.910 --> 00:11:00.110
my kid is asking for this
quinoa salad that you made.

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:02.080
My kid is asking for
these kale chips.

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:03.450
Can you-- how do I make them?

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:04.057
What is this?

00:11:04.057 --> 00:11:04.890
CARLA HALL: Exactly.

00:11:04.890 --> 00:11:06.110
HILLARY BERGH: So
it's really cool.

00:11:06.110 --> 00:11:07.318
CARLA HALL: It's really cool.

00:11:07.318 --> 00:11:09.500
And that's what's so
important about kids

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:11.340
being involved in food.

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:13.930
Because what happens,
I think, as adults,

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:16.280
we tend to put them
in these boxes.

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:18.050
But when kids have
an experience,

00:11:18.050 --> 00:11:19.970
and they take that
experience home,

00:11:19.970 --> 00:11:22.890
then they're broadening
their parents'

00:11:22.890 --> 00:11:24.280
idea of what they would want.

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:26.363
And so then, the parents
are getting those things.

00:11:26.363 --> 00:11:28.940
And it's this big cycle
that should continue.

00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:30.250
And it's so beautiful to see.

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:32.110
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah,
it is, for sure.

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:34.970
So you alluded a little bit
to TV a few minutes ago.

00:11:34.970 --> 00:11:37.660
What are some secrets you
might be able to share with us?

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:39.810
Because, is there
really cooking going on?

00:11:39.810 --> 00:11:42.370
CARLA HALL: There's
really cooking.

00:11:42.370 --> 00:11:44.300
Some things not good.

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:45.760
Some things are not a winner.

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:48.840
There are some things,
and-- so we actually

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:49.950
do cook in real time.

00:11:49.950 --> 00:11:52.050
And some of the things
are so delicious.

00:11:52.050 --> 00:11:54.080
And a lot of times, you'll
see us start a dish.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:55.650
And then there's a
commercial break,

00:11:55.650 --> 00:11:58.889
and we finish cooking that dish
during the commercial break.

00:11:58.889 --> 00:12:00.180
And we come back and we eat it.

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:02.580
Especially things that
cook very quickly.

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:04.490
I mean, stews, you
can't do that with.

00:12:04.490 --> 00:12:06.730
So you put them together,
and there's a slot.

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:10.270
But for the most part, we
really try to do those quickly.

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:12.644
Those dishes that cook
quickly, we are eating them.

00:12:12.644 --> 00:12:14.060
As a matter of
fact, we've kind of

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:15.351
got a little snobbish about it.

00:12:15.351 --> 00:12:18.120
So the culinary team will
bring some of those dishes

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:18.954
from the kitchen.

00:12:18.954 --> 00:12:20.370
But they were
cooked, because they

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:22.800
have to stagger everything
and make them ahead of time.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:24.770
And we're like, oh,
I don't want that.

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:27.540
I want the dish that
was just cooked,

00:12:27.540 --> 00:12:29.880
that's hot and delicious,
that Mario made.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.182
No offense to the kitchen
staff, but, you know.

00:12:32.182 --> 00:12:33.890
HILLARY BERGH: Well,
that's good to know,

00:12:33.890 --> 00:12:36.660
because that shows you how
quickly you can make something

00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:37.290
at home, right?

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:38.040
CARLA HALL: Right.

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:40.400
I mean the "5 in 5"
that Michael does,

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:41.940
his little segment
called "5 in 5."

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:44.950
So it's five ingredients,
five minutes or less,

00:12:44.950 --> 00:12:48.320
and he makes it right there.

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:50.350
So if it takes Michael
five minutes-- I mean,

00:12:50.350 --> 00:12:52.570
maybe it's going to take
somebody at home 20 minutes.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:56.660
But still, that's fast, to
get dinner on the table.

00:12:56.660 --> 00:12:59.230
And sometimes, his
pan will be too hot,

00:12:59.230 --> 00:13:01.780
and there are all kinds of
antics that are going on.

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:03.280
And Mario is like, yeah, chef.

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:05.310
You haven't had the pasta in,
and you have one minute left.

00:13:05.310 --> 00:13:07.170
Yeah, let's see if
you're going to make it.

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:09.610
But it's still really
fun to show people

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:12.177
that they can have a really
quick meal under 30 minutes.

00:13:12.177 --> 00:13:13.510
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah, absolutely.

00:13:13.510 --> 00:13:16.150
And I know that all of you
are working long hours.

00:13:16.150 --> 00:13:18.020
I'm certainly
working long hours.

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:20.060
So little tips and
tricks, anything else

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:21.160
you might share with us?

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:23.170
So we need to watch the
show for the "5 in 5."

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:25.045
CARLA HALL: Yeah, you
need to watch the show.

00:13:27.465 --> 00:13:28.630
Here's a funny story.

00:13:28.630 --> 00:13:31.909
It has nothing to do with food.

00:13:31.909 --> 00:13:33.450
HILLARY BERGH: We're
ready, I'm sure.

00:13:37.310 --> 00:13:41.260
CARLA HALL: So when
the show first started,

00:13:41.260 --> 00:13:45.070
I had to get used to-- the
transition from "Top Chef"

00:13:45.070 --> 00:13:46.940
to where I'm just
cooking and there happens

00:13:46.940 --> 00:13:51.260
to be a camera-- to actually
hosting a show where you're

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:53.080
cooking, you're
talking to a guest,

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:56.040
you're telling the audience
a little bit about yourself,

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:57.390
all of these things.

00:13:57.390 --> 00:13:58.220
You're juggling.

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:00.060
It's really harder
than you think.

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:02.370
I mean, it's multitasking
like nobody's business.

00:14:02.370 --> 00:14:05.250
And we have found,
and studies of shown,

00:14:05.250 --> 00:14:08.196
that multitasking
really doesn't work.

00:14:08.196 --> 00:14:11.024
But it's kind of boring when
you have to cook something

00:14:11.024 --> 00:14:12.690
and you're just like,
whatever, hold on,

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:14.481
and you're just focusing
on that one thing.

00:14:14.481 --> 00:14:16.240
So you have to multitask, OK.

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:21.520
So I have an IFB in my ear
where the executive producer

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:22.340
talks in your ear.

00:14:22.340 --> 00:14:23.630
And he helps you go along.

00:14:23.630 --> 00:14:27.540
If you need to move on,
he will say, hey, move on.

00:14:27.540 --> 00:14:32.180
He'll say, "great"
and then you move on.

00:14:32.180 --> 00:14:34.030
"Fantastic," you move on.

00:14:34.030 --> 00:14:36.400
So this was in the
beginning before I'm

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:37.935
used to someone
talking in my ear.

00:14:37.935 --> 00:14:39.490
Usually, if I hear
voices in my head,

00:14:39.490 --> 00:14:44.470
they're mine, not somebody
else's with this deep voice

00:14:44.470 --> 00:14:46.150
with an Australian accent.

00:14:46.150 --> 00:14:48.330
So I have the IFB.

00:14:48.330 --> 00:14:51.550
I'm actually interviewing
this person, I'm cooking,

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:54.030
and I'm doing this egg dish.

00:14:54.030 --> 00:14:58.210
And he just keeps
saying "egg," "egg."

00:14:58.210 --> 00:15:00.430
And he just keeps saying it.

00:15:00.430 --> 00:15:01.980
That's all he's saying, "egg."

00:15:01.980 --> 00:15:03.310
So I'm hearing "egg."

00:15:03.310 --> 00:15:07.040
And let say I'm interviewing
you, and I'm like, "egg."

00:15:07.040 --> 00:15:09.690
He says "egg." "Egg."

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:11.125
I'm literally
saying it out loud.

00:15:11.125 --> 00:15:12.590
I just keep saying "egg."

00:15:12.590 --> 00:15:14.860
And then, I look
over at Michael.

00:15:14.860 --> 00:15:18.220
He's like this,
cracking up laughing.

00:15:18.220 --> 00:15:20.290
Because I'm like, why
does he keep saying "egg"?

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:23.590
He doesn't say, "put the
egg," "don't forget the egg."

00:15:23.590 --> 00:15:26.450
So he just says this
one word, "egg."

00:15:26.450 --> 00:15:28.720
So I'm like, you need
to give me more words.

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:30.480
OK, so keep that in your head.

00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:32.280
So then, let's fast forward.

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:34.280
Now it's season two.

00:15:34.280 --> 00:15:35.970
And this is what
I get in my ear.

00:15:35.970 --> 00:15:38.450
"Carla, well, you know,
what I think you should do

00:15:38.450 --> 00:15:40.620
is talk to them about--
you know, there's an egg."

00:15:40.620 --> 00:15:43.550
I'm like, why are you
giving me so many words?

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:45.912
He's having a
conversation in my ear.

00:15:45.912 --> 00:15:49.280
I'm like-- And so sometimes,
if you watch the show,

00:15:49.280 --> 00:15:50.180
I'm like this.

00:15:58.410 --> 00:16:03.000
Because I'm answering
those voices in my head,

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:04.910
which is kind of crazy.

00:16:04.910 --> 00:16:06.290
The food is usually really good.

00:16:06.290 --> 00:16:07.050
You can tell.

00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:08.860
I don't fake it.

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:12.019
If I don't like something,
my face really can't--

00:16:12.019 --> 00:16:13.810
HILLARY BERGH: It's
not going to hold back.

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:14.768
CARLA HALL: It doesn't.

00:16:14.768 --> 00:16:23.060
I'm like-- So most of the things
that Mario makes are delicious.

00:16:23.060 --> 00:16:25.890
I love me some Mario Batali.

00:16:25.890 --> 00:16:31.960
But one time, at band
camp, Mario made this dish.

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:33.960
It was panettone.

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:34.700
Delicious.

00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:38.390
He made a French toast with
panettone with maple syrup.

00:16:38.390 --> 00:16:39.080
Delicious.

00:16:39.080 --> 00:16:41.124
And you know, Mario makes
really good meatballs

00:16:41.124 --> 00:16:42.040
with the tomato sauce.

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:45.110
He actually has a tomato
sauce that you can buy.

00:16:45.110 --> 00:16:46.610
Delicious.

00:16:46.610 --> 00:16:48.220
But this particular
day, he decided

00:16:48.220 --> 00:16:50.610
to take that meatball,
and that tomato sauce,

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:53.520
and that beautiful panettone
with that maple syrup,

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:54.380
do a mashup.

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:55.400
HILLARY BERGH: Uh-oh.

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:57.536
CARLA HALL: Oh, no.

00:16:57.536 --> 00:16:59.800
I'm sure they don't
eat it in Italy.

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:02.730
And I'm very sure they should
not have it here in America.

00:17:02.730 --> 00:17:03.590
It was not a winner.

00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:09.308
And I was like--
Yeah, it wasn't good.

00:17:09.308 --> 00:17:10.849
HILLARY BERGH: Did
he really like it?

00:17:10.849 --> 00:17:11.890
He thought it was--

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:13.265
CARLA HALL: I was
looking at him,

00:17:13.265 --> 00:17:19.619
and I said-- I said, do
you really like this?

00:17:19.619 --> 00:17:23.410
Because when Mario doesn't
like something, he's like this.

00:17:23.410 --> 00:17:30.320
Like that one time that Clinton
decided to make an eggnog.

00:17:30.320 --> 00:17:33.250
And with raw eggs.

00:17:33.250 --> 00:17:34.200
OK.

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:38.420
And Mario's like, I'm
not having that eggnog.

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:39.000
Right.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:44.140
But everybody else had some.

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:49.620
And on the way home, if
you were on the train--

00:17:49.620 --> 00:17:50.899
HILLARY BERGH: Uh-oh.

00:17:50.899 --> 00:17:52.440
CARLA HALL: --you
were having issues.

00:17:56.210 --> 00:17:58.460
We were all texting
each other, saying,

00:17:58.460 --> 00:17:59.460
I had to take a meeting.

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:01.460
I had to run to the
bathroom and take a meeting.

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:04.110
That's code for having to
go to the bathroom for us.

00:18:04.110 --> 00:18:05.240
And it wasn't good.

00:18:05.240 --> 00:18:06.865
Mario said, I told
you guys not to have

00:18:06.865 --> 00:18:11.730
that eggnog with those fresh
eggs that weren't so fresh.

00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:14.230
HILLARY BERGH: Maybe if they
had been from someone's chicken

00:18:14.230 --> 00:18:14.938
in the backyard--

00:18:14.938 --> 00:18:16.110
CARLA HALL: Exactly.

00:18:16.110 --> 00:18:18.574
Like "Portlandia,"
you knew that chicken.

00:18:18.574 --> 00:18:21.790
You're like, is that from Sam?

00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:24.250
Sam, did you cluck
that chicken out?

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:25.470
Yes, exactly.

00:18:25.470 --> 00:18:27.273
But no, we didn't
know those chickens.

00:18:27.273 --> 00:18:28.860
HILLARY BERGH:
Nope, that's risky.

00:18:28.860 --> 00:18:29.399
Raw chicken.

00:18:29.399 --> 00:18:30.440
CARLA HALL: Risky, risky.

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:33.190
A word to the wise.

00:18:33.190 --> 00:18:36.070
HILLARY BERGH: So, comfort
food, there's always

00:18:36.070 --> 00:18:39.490
this stigma of it's
heavy, it's greasy.

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:42.840
But you take a very healthy
approach here, which I like.

00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:44.960
I have a very healthy
approach in my cafe.

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:49.300
And people that haven't
eaten my food yet-- or maybe

00:18:49.300 --> 00:18:52.060
you can relate to
before you were famous--

00:18:52.060 --> 00:18:55.990
and they look at me and they
go, but you're so skinny.

00:18:55.990 --> 00:18:57.205
Your food must not be good.

00:18:57.205 --> 00:18:57.490
CARLA HALL: Girl, I know.

00:18:57.490 --> 00:18:58.550
Never trust a skinny chef.

00:18:58.550 --> 00:18:59.942
You get that all
the time, right?

00:18:59.942 --> 00:19:00.413
HILLARY BERGH: Yes.

00:19:00.413 --> 00:19:01.830
CARLA HALL: Do
you eat your food?

00:19:01.830 --> 00:19:02.100
HILLARY BERGH: Right?

00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:03.310
CARLA HALL: I know, I know.

00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:03.990
I get it, too.

00:19:03.990 --> 00:19:04.360
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah?

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:05.443
CARLA HALL: I get it, too.

00:19:05.443 --> 00:19:07.600
HILLARY BERGH: So
what do you do?

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:10.030
CARLA HALL: The funny
thing is people,

00:19:10.030 --> 00:19:12.790
oftentimes, they say, oh, you
have this healthy approach

00:19:12.790 --> 00:19:13.870
to your food.

00:19:13.870 --> 00:19:15.740
And I don't think
of it that way.

00:19:15.740 --> 00:19:17.860
I think that it's
just how I cook.

00:19:17.860 --> 00:19:19.430
I want to taste the food.

00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:21.540
I want to taste the ingredients.

00:19:21.540 --> 00:19:23.850
I want to taste the
vegetables that I'm using.

00:19:23.850 --> 00:19:26.112
So I don't want to put
a lot of fat into it.

00:19:26.112 --> 00:19:27.570
I don't want to
put a lot of bacon.

00:19:27.570 --> 00:19:29.100
If I'm having bacon,
I'm having bacon.

00:19:29.100 --> 00:19:30.933
But if I'm having grains,
I'm having grains.

00:19:30.933 --> 00:19:32.890
If I'm having hot
water cornbread, which

00:19:32.890 --> 00:19:35.495
you guys probably
know nothing about,

00:19:35.495 --> 00:19:36.870
you can have a
little bit of fat.

00:19:36.870 --> 00:19:38.650
Has anybody had hot
water cornbread?

00:19:38.650 --> 00:19:39.150
What?

00:19:39.150 --> 00:19:40.629
Where are your
people from, girl?

00:19:40.629 --> 00:19:41.462
AUDIENCE: Louisiana.

00:19:41.462 --> 00:19:43.010
CARLA HALL: Ah!

00:19:43.010 --> 00:19:44.640
OK, so hot water cornbread.

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:48.069
Let's just take a little
time out, a little break.

00:19:48.069 --> 00:19:51.880
Hot water cornbread
is white cornmeal.

00:19:51.880 --> 00:19:54.790
And you have a
little bit of fat,

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:58.150
and some salt, and no sugar.

00:19:58.150 --> 00:20:00.700
By the way, Southerners,
for the most part,

00:20:00.700 --> 00:20:02.550
if they're real
Southerners, they

00:20:02.550 --> 00:20:05.110
like everything sweet
but their cornbread.

00:20:05.110 --> 00:20:08.560
It's OK to drop a whole five
pounds of sugar in your tea.

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:09.450
That's fine.

00:20:09.450 --> 00:20:11.840
But you do not put
it in the cornbread.

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:13.482
And then, a little
bit of bacon fat.

00:20:13.482 --> 00:20:14.440
You know, bacon grease.

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:16.070
And you make this
mush with hot water.

00:20:16.070 --> 00:20:20.280
You make a mush, and then you
make them into little patties

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:21.010
and you fry it.

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:23.840
So inside, it's very tender, and
the outside is kind of crispy

00:20:23.840 --> 00:20:26.550
because it fries
in the shallow oil.

00:20:26.550 --> 00:20:29.240
And that's what you
use with-- you have it

00:20:29.240 --> 00:20:32.840
with beans and collard
greens and stews,

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:33.930
because it's for sopping.

00:20:33.930 --> 00:20:35.721
Which is why we don't
have sweet cornbread,

00:20:35.721 --> 00:20:37.972
because it's for sopping.

00:20:37.972 --> 00:20:39.430
Why did I start
talking about this?

00:20:39.430 --> 00:20:40.940
HILLARY BERGH: We were
talking about healthy food

00:20:40.940 --> 00:20:42.460
and the healthy approach.

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:44.200
But fat is still good.

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:45.080
There's fat in here.

00:20:45.080 --> 00:20:46.200
Fat is good, but--

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:48.970
CARLA HALL: Fat is good, but
I want to taste the food.

00:20:48.970 --> 00:20:49.940
I want to taste it.

00:20:49.940 --> 00:20:57.210
And so my grandmother, who was
born in 1908, at a time when

00:20:57.210 --> 00:21:02.200
people were having
a lot of hog jaws

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:06.220
and all of that in her food,
her husband-- my grandfather,

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:09.010
[? Doc-- ?] had
high blood pressure.

00:21:09.010 --> 00:21:11.610
And so she took that
out of her food.

00:21:11.610 --> 00:21:14.810
So I grew up having a lighter
version of Southern food.

00:21:14.810 --> 00:21:18.880
And I think that
comfort food for me

00:21:18.880 --> 00:21:22.230
is all the food that you
might have in your kitchen,

00:21:22.230 --> 00:21:24.870
where somebody who loves
you is making for you.

00:21:24.870 --> 00:21:26.510
And so, when you're
feeling low, you

00:21:26.510 --> 00:21:28.920
go back to those food
memories for that thing.

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:30.340
And so it changes for everybody.

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:33.575
I mean, in San Francisco,
it may be your cioppino.

00:21:33.575 --> 00:21:35.300
And that doesn't have
a lot of fat in it.

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:37.540
It's a seafood stew, right?

00:21:37.540 --> 00:21:38.960
But it's different
for everybody.

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:44.210
And I wanted to celebrate what
could be comfort food for one

00:21:44.210 --> 00:21:47.427
and a delicacy for
another, or whatever.

00:21:47.427 --> 00:21:48.885
And that's with
this book is about.

00:21:48.885 --> 00:21:50.468
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah,
that's very cool.

00:21:50.468 --> 00:21:53.730
So, as a female in
our industry, we're

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:56.690
