00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:13.990
Can you tell us a little bit
about sustainable seafood

00:30:13.990 --> 00:30:15.870
and your take on that?

00:30:15.870 --> 00:30:18.900
CARLA HALL: So this event,
Cooking for Solutions,

00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:19.680
is so amazing.

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.820
I think I've done it, this
is probably my third time.

00:30:22.820 --> 00:30:24.950
And I skipped a couple years.

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:28.020
But when you're in the
Monterey Bay, when you're here,

00:30:28.020 --> 00:30:30.200
you're reminded why
you're doing all of this.

00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:33.010
And I think
California has sort of

00:30:33.010 --> 00:30:37.240
been the lead in telling
the rest of the country how

00:30:37.240 --> 00:30:41.580
to conserve and how
to appreciate our land

00:30:41.580 --> 00:30:44.000
and not take it for granted.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.890
And so, when you go
to your Whole Foods,

00:30:48.890 --> 00:30:53.500
and you see the fish that's
on the avoid list, the red.

00:30:53.500 --> 00:30:56.090
And then you have the
yellow, and then the green.

00:30:56.090 --> 00:30:57.750
It's so important.

00:30:57.750 --> 00:30:59.640
And it's actually
doing this event

00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:03.400
that I started thinking
about what fishes to buy.

00:31:03.400 --> 00:31:05.530
Because you kind of forget.

00:31:05.530 --> 00:31:08.840
Because they're there doesn't
mean that you have to buy them.

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:13.650
And sea bass, I
had to just tell--

00:31:13.650 --> 00:31:16.620
I mean, in this industry,
I think, when we cook

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:23.210
and we see the food
rules, so to speak,

00:31:23.210 --> 00:31:25.780
but we forget that the
lay person doesn't know.

00:31:25.780 --> 00:31:28.820
So my sister, who
loves Chilean sea bass,

00:31:28.820 --> 00:31:32.010
I have to go and tell
her, well, Kim, you really

00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:32.940
shouldn't have that.

00:31:32.940 --> 00:31:35.240
Honestly, if you go to a
restaurant and they have it,

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:38.340
then they probably are
having a lot of other fish

00:31:38.340 --> 00:31:40.680
that they should not
have on their menu.

00:31:40.680 --> 00:31:42.980
And I would like for you
not to go there, please.

00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:51.080
And it's our responsibility
in being chefs and working

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:54.417
with food to lead the
charge and tell people what

00:31:54.417 --> 00:31:55.750
they should and should not have.

00:31:55.750 --> 00:31:57.600
And it starts with us.

00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:01.840
So I take that responsibility
very seriously,

00:32:01.840 --> 00:32:05.920
as I take the responsibility
of cooking for someone very

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:06.770
seriously.

00:32:06.770 --> 00:32:09.970
Because, if I'm in a bad
mood-- and I say this--

00:32:09.970 --> 00:32:12.560
if you're in a bad mood, the
only thing you should make

00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:15.072
is a reservation.

00:32:15.072 --> 00:32:17.620
And at that point, you pray
that whoever made your food

00:32:17.620 --> 00:32:19.780
there is in a good
mood, because you'll

00:32:19.780 --> 00:32:22.480
think it's the blue fish that's
off, and it was the chef.

00:32:22.480 --> 00:32:23.640
HILLARY BERGH: That's true.

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:26.410
The energy that's in
the kitchen definitely

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:28.240
translates into the food.

00:32:28.240 --> 00:32:29.290
Absolutely.

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:30.170
Cook with love.

00:32:30.170 --> 00:32:31.570
Always cook with love.

00:32:31.570 --> 00:32:32.260
Yes.

00:32:32.260 --> 00:32:35.840
So you were on NPR recently.

00:32:35.840 --> 00:32:38.330
And one of the things that
really caught my attention

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:39.750
was your take on salt.

00:32:39.750 --> 00:32:42.510
And I loved the
compliments versus insults

00:32:42.510 --> 00:32:44.150
that you referred to.

00:32:44.150 --> 00:32:45.692
Can you share with them that?

00:32:45.692 --> 00:32:47.400
CARLA HALL: Yes, let
me pick somebody out

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:49.120
to share this with.

00:32:49.120 --> 00:32:50.310
Sir?

00:32:50.310 --> 00:32:51.210
OK.

00:32:51.210 --> 00:32:52.120
So what's your name?

00:32:52.120 --> 00:32:52.710
AUDIENCE: Aaron.

00:32:52.710 --> 00:32:53.460
CARLA HALL: Aaron?

00:32:53.460 --> 00:32:54.010
All right.

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:57.200
So Aaron, are you old
enough to have gone back

00:32:57.200 --> 00:32:58.840
for your class reunion?

00:32:58.840 --> 00:32:59.430
OK, great.

00:32:59.430 --> 00:33:01.595
I don't know.

00:33:01.595 --> 00:33:02.970
I went to my class
reunion, and I

00:33:02.970 --> 00:33:04.720
realized that Santa
Claus was in my class.

00:33:04.720 --> 00:33:07.330
I'm like, whoa.

00:33:07.330 --> 00:33:11.115
So Aaron, you go back to your
high school class reunion,

00:33:11.115 --> 00:33:13.810
and they say, oh,
Aaron, you look so good.

00:33:13.810 --> 00:33:14.980
Oh, let me just back up.

00:33:14.980 --> 00:33:19.040
I call salt compliments,
like Hillary said.

00:33:19.040 --> 00:33:20.839
But too many compliments
is an insult.

00:33:20.839 --> 00:33:21.630
So that's the idea.

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:25.750
But to get people to get
their head around it, you say,

00:33:25.750 --> 00:33:26.950
Aaron you look really good.

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:27.950
And you're like, thanks.

00:33:27.950 --> 00:33:29.000
You're like, yeah.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:30.510
And you're smiling
at this point.

00:33:30.510 --> 00:33:32.580
And they're like, no,
you look really good.

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:34.236
Have you guys seen Aaron?

00:33:34.236 --> 00:33:35.110
Doesn't he look good?

00:33:35.110 --> 00:33:38.540
Oh, my god, you look so good.

00:33:38.540 --> 00:33:41.118
Oh, you look good.

00:33:41.118 --> 00:33:43.390
So then, at this point,
you're thinking, well damn.

00:33:43.390 --> 00:33:45.955
What did I look like before?

00:33:45.955 --> 00:33:46.775
I mean, right?

00:33:49.310 --> 00:33:52.000
Because again, too many
compliments is an insult.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:53.810
And the same thing with salt.

00:33:53.810 --> 00:33:57.150
Salt is perfect if it
is used in moderation

00:33:57.150 --> 00:33:59.090
and it goes into the food.

00:33:59.090 --> 00:34:01.539
And as you're cooking, you
add salt into the food.

00:34:01.539 --> 00:34:03.580
Like the church in the
steeple, that whole thing.

00:34:03.580 --> 00:34:06.200
So the salt has to go into
the fiber of the food.

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:08.219
But if you use too much,
you can't take it out,

00:34:08.219 --> 00:34:09.429
and it ruins the dish.

00:34:09.429 --> 00:34:13.864
And sometimes, people
may not use salt,

00:34:13.864 --> 00:34:15.280
and they will put
it on the table.

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:16.489
And they're very proud of that.

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:18.154
They're like, oh, I don't
use salt in my food.

00:34:18.154 --> 00:34:18.903
It's on the table.

00:34:18.903 --> 00:34:20.800
And I'm like, thank you
for letting me know,

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:23.064
I don't have to go to the table.

00:34:23.064 --> 00:34:26.500
Because when you add salt,
and you're putting salt

00:34:26.500 --> 00:34:28.147
on top of the food,
it's only on top.

00:34:28.147 --> 00:34:29.480
So it's not going into the food.

00:34:29.480 --> 00:34:31.813
So you keep adding salt and
adding salt and adding salt.

00:34:31.813 --> 00:34:32.870
And then you over-salt.

00:34:32.870 --> 00:34:35.620
And then all of a
sudden, you have

00:34:35.620 --> 00:34:36.864
this dish that you can't eat.

00:34:36.864 --> 00:34:39.920
Or when you buy processed
foods, what you have said

00:34:39.920 --> 00:34:42.659
is, thank you for
salting my food for me.

00:34:42.659 --> 00:34:44.730
You've given your power
away, because they've

00:34:44.730 --> 00:34:45.949
salted it for you.

00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:48.824
And so this is what I
always try to tell people.

00:34:48.824 --> 00:34:50.199
When you're cooking
from scratch,

00:34:50.199 --> 00:34:52.014
and it looks like chefs
use a lot of salt.

00:34:52.014 --> 00:34:54.150
But you're cooking from
scratch, and I know,

00:34:54.150 --> 00:34:55.394
and you're like, let it rain.

00:34:55.394 --> 00:34:57.480
And in Mario, it's like roar.

00:34:57.480 --> 00:34:59.510
And the food is dusty.

00:34:59.510 --> 00:35:04.630
It's like a covering of
white dust on your food.

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:07.180
But if it's a big piece
of meat, it can take that.

00:35:07.180 --> 00:35:08.130
It can take that salt.

00:35:08.130 --> 00:35:11.110
But again, too much salt--
too many spices-- too much

00:35:11.110 --> 00:35:13.690
of anything is an insult
because you're not

00:35:13.690 --> 00:35:15.787
tasting the food
itself, now you're only

00:35:15.787 --> 00:35:17.370
tasting the things
that you put on it.

00:35:17.370 --> 00:35:18.244
HILLARY BERGH: Right.

00:35:18.244 --> 00:35:20.280
Just enough to enhance
what's already going on.

00:35:20.280 --> 00:35:20.650
CARLA HALL: Right, exactly.

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:21.310
Nature.

00:35:21.310 --> 00:35:22.393
And this is another thing.

00:35:22.393 --> 00:35:26.570
And this is why in a cookbook--
speaking of nature-- nature

00:35:26.570 --> 00:35:32.100
gives you this ingredient
the decimals or whatever

00:35:32.100 --> 00:35:35.440
and it changes so the
terrorists may be sweet today

00:35:35.440 --> 00:35:36.750
and tomorrow they're not sweet.

00:35:36.750 --> 00:35:39.770
So that's why it's so
important to taste your food

00:35:39.770 --> 00:35:43.040
because you can't
read in the cookbook,

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:45.970
oh, a 1/2 teaspoon of
salt and then, well,

00:35:45.970 --> 00:35:47.410
hey, her food
doesn't taste great.

00:35:47.410 --> 00:35:50.550
Because you're using ingredients
and you have to kind of taste

00:35:50.550 --> 00:35:53.220
to determine what
that needs that day.

00:35:53.220 --> 00:35:54.480
HILLARY BERGH: Yes.

00:35:54.480 --> 00:35:55.563
To taste.

00:35:55.563 --> 00:35:56.290
CARLA HALL: Yeah.

00:35:56.290 --> 00:35:57.164
HILLARY BERGH: Right.

