So they'll come in and say,
Carla, we're doing a show.

00:40:43.680 --> 00:40:44.880
"Batter up" is the theme.

00:40:44.880 --> 00:40:47.260
And so we are doing
something with batter.

00:40:47.260 --> 00:40:50.410
And Michael is already doing
something with the meat.

00:40:50.410 --> 00:40:51.710
Mario's doing this.

00:40:51.710 --> 00:40:53.060
Can you do a dessert?

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:54.950
So there's that part of it.

00:40:59.670 --> 00:41:04.160
Like I said, it's so hard to
cook and talk to somebody.

00:41:04.160 --> 00:41:07.320
And you want to make
a good dish and relate

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:11.510
to the people who
are watching you.

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:14.670
That was the biggest
transition for me.

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:17.870
And so it just
comes with practice.

00:41:17.870 --> 00:41:20.810
But it also helps to--
like in the beginning,

00:41:20.810 --> 00:41:24.690
I would read through the
entire script of the show,

00:41:24.690 --> 00:41:28.270
and then whoever we had coming
on the show, I felt like Oprah.

00:41:28.270 --> 00:41:32.040
In my head I said, this is
Oprah reading a book the night

00:41:32.040 --> 00:41:33.895
before she sees a guest.

00:41:33.895 --> 00:41:36.020
So then you know that you're
going to have a guest.

00:41:36.020 --> 00:41:38.680
So you want to know a
little bit about them.

00:41:38.680 --> 00:41:40.870
And so you watch
all these clips.

00:41:40.870 --> 00:41:43.460
You go down this rabbit
hole of who they are.

00:41:43.460 --> 00:41:46.060
And you want to have
some information just

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:47.492
to connect with them.

00:41:47.492 --> 00:41:48.450
So there's all of that.

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:51.170
And that's what I'm doing after
2 o'clock, when I say I'm off

00:41:51.170 --> 00:41:53.420
but I'm not really off.

00:41:53.420 --> 00:41:56.300
So just absorbing
all that information

00:41:56.300 --> 00:41:59.150
and being 50 and having
that hormone that

00:41:59.150 --> 00:42:02.170
takes your mind
away is hard, too.

00:42:02.170 --> 00:42:03.770
I don't remember a darn thing.

00:42:03.770 --> 00:42:06.470
I mean I'm like, I have three
things to tell you, one, blah,

00:42:06.470 --> 00:42:10.610
blah, blah, two, blah,
blah, blah, three-- three?

00:42:10.610 --> 00:42:12.100
I guess it wasn't important.

00:42:12.100 --> 00:42:13.070
So all of that.

00:42:13.070 --> 00:42:15.360
So it's a balance of all that.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:18.600
But the best thing that
you may or may not see,

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:20.940
is that we have the
support of each other.

00:42:20.940 --> 00:42:23.190
So let's say I do forget
something but Michael's right

00:42:23.190 --> 00:42:23.689
there.

00:42:23.689 --> 00:42:26.030
He's like, oh, Carla, what
about blah, blah, blah?

00:42:26.030 --> 00:42:29.890
And then so we have that between
each other, which is amazing.

00:42:29.890 --> 00:42:34.540
If it wasn't for
Michael and Mario

00:42:34.540 --> 00:42:37.390
specifically about how
to balance that food

00:42:37.390 --> 00:42:39.939
and doing the demo
and interview,

00:42:39.939 --> 00:42:41.230
I would have been totally lost.

00:42:41.230 --> 00:42:42.450
I really relied on them.

00:42:42.450 --> 00:42:44.680
Clinton had also done
a lot of television.

00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:47.490
And the thing that
he told me was

00:42:47.490 --> 00:42:49.760
to be authentic, to be yourself.

00:42:49.760 --> 00:42:54.470
And what a lot of people may not
know, after the first season,

00:42:54.470 --> 00:42:55.970
I went to a media trainer.

00:42:55.970 --> 00:43:00.230
And it really wasn't
to learn how to do TV,

00:43:00.230 --> 00:43:04.060
it was trying to be the best me
I could be in front of a camera

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:06.150
and not have those inhibitions.

00:43:06.150 --> 00:43:07.730
HILLARY BERGH: Ah, cool.

00:43:07.730 --> 00:43:08.230
Let's see.

00:43:08.230 --> 00:43:09.600
I think we had
another question here.

00:43:09.600 --> 00:43:11.100
We got the microphone up to you.

00:43:15.300 --> 00:43:17.870
AUDIENCE: So with
a lot of new cooks,

00:43:17.870 --> 00:43:20.820
they seem to be really
intimidated by the oven,

00:43:20.820 --> 00:43:23.320
but right away
eager to cook eggs.

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:25.320
Eggs are so
technically difficult--

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:26.420
CARLA HALL: Dude!

00:43:26.420 --> 00:43:28.540
AUDIENCE: Why do you think
this is so backwards?

00:43:28.540 --> 00:43:30.832
I mean, sticking a
boneless, skinless chicken

00:43:30.832 --> 00:43:32.415
breast in the oven
and clicking Broil,

00:43:32.415 --> 00:43:35.050
you have long stretches of time.

00:43:35.050 --> 00:43:37.270
You can be off by five
minutes, it's not a big deal.

00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:37.515
CARLA HALL: Yeah, it is.

00:43:37.515 --> 00:43:40.200
AUDIENCE: Eggs, it's like
five seconds, it's over.

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:42.417
Why do you think things
are backwards like that

00:43:42.417 --> 00:43:43.000
for new shows?

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:46.440
CARLA HALL: When I was
working in the kitchen

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:52.030
and I was running a kitchen,
and I was having to hire people,

00:43:52.030 --> 00:43:55.230
I would have them make
an omelette, eggs.

00:43:55.230 --> 00:43:57.050
And I had them make
an omelette because I

00:43:57.050 --> 00:44:00.420
could tell how they held
a pan, how cleanly they

00:44:00.420 --> 00:44:03.470
worked, how they
use their tools.

00:44:03.470 --> 00:44:06.440
It's a lot of finesse in
something very simple.

00:44:06.440 --> 00:44:11.220
And I'm like, can do
the simple very well?

00:44:11.220 --> 00:44:14.600
When I go to an ice cream
store, I want their vanilla.

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:16.980
When I go to a restaurant, I
want their roasted chicken.

00:44:16.980 --> 00:44:18.540
Can you do the
simple really well?

00:44:18.540 --> 00:44:20.910
Because a lot of
smoke and mirrors,

00:44:20.910 --> 00:44:28.390
you can slide under the
wire with all of this.

00:44:28.390 --> 00:44:31.574
The presentation and
sauces and your food

00:44:31.574 --> 00:44:32.990
on one side of the
plate, thinking

00:44:32.990 --> 00:44:36.300
that they left the
rest of it off.

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:39.930
You can do a lot, but can
you do the simple well?

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:43.160
And with eggs, are they
seasoned perfectly?

00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:44.230
Are they fluffy?

00:44:44.230 --> 00:44:46.630
Is the omelette
coming out of the pan?

00:44:46.630 --> 00:44:48.550
Is it all tucked nicely?

00:44:48.550 --> 00:44:50.690
So in culinary
school, you actually

00:44:50.690 --> 00:44:54.470
spend about a month
on eggs, eggs alone.

00:44:54.470 --> 00:44:58.690
I think with cooking
something like chicken,

00:44:58.690 --> 00:45:03.330
people are afraid of it, I think
because it goes into this box.

00:45:03.330 --> 00:45:05.261
It goes in there,
and I guess they

00:45:05.261 --> 00:45:06.760
don't know what's
going to come out.

00:45:06.760 --> 00:45:10.840
It's like this magic box.

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:12.914
But I disagree that
you have five or 10

00:45:12.914 --> 00:45:14.580
minutes with that
chicken because people

00:45:14.580 --> 00:45:16.450
will cook that chicken to death.

00:45:16.450 --> 00:45:19.373
People are afraid
of raw chicken.

00:45:19.373 --> 00:45:21.490
I mean, they are
so afraid and they

00:45:21.490 --> 00:45:24.780
will cook it until it's dust.

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.280
HILLARY BERGH: The
health department

00:45:26.280 --> 00:45:30.700
says 165, but at home pull
it out a little earlier.

00:45:30.700 --> 00:45:33.967
It's going to continue to carry
over cooking on your counter.

00:45:33.967 --> 00:45:35.550
CARLA HALL: We have
two words for you.

00:45:35.550 --> 00:45:37.010
Residual heat.

00:45:37.010 --> 00:45:37.892
HILLARY BERGH: Yes.

00:45:37.892 --> 00:45:39.599
CARLA HALL: Yes.

00:45:39.599 --> 00:45:40.640
HILLARY BERGH: All right.

00:45:40.640 --> 00:45:42.340
Let's get the-- oh, there we go.

00:45:42.340 --> 00:45:42.970
There's another [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:42.970 --> 00:45:43.850
AUDIENCE: So I have
a question for you.

00:45:43.850 --> 00:45:45.516
There was an article
in "The New Yorker"

00:45:45.516 --> 00:45:49.335
this week about this crazy
dinner they had a WD~50.

00:45:49.335 --> 00:45:51.460
They had three chefs fly
in from all over the world

00:45:51.460 --> 00:45:54.360
to basically create all
their interpretations

00:45:54.360 --> 00:45:56.230
of their favorite dishes ever.

00:45:56.230 --> 00:45:58.345
What's the best meal
that you've ever had?

00:45:58.345 --> 00:46:00.790
Because you work with
so many phenomenal chefs

00:46:00.790 --> 00:46:01.860
over the years.

00:46:01.860 --> 00:46:04.810
What is the most memorable
meal that you've ever done?

00:46:04.810 --> 00:46:07.810
CARLA HALL: Oh wow, what is the
most memorable meal I've had?

00:46:07.810 --> 00:46:08.190
HILLARY BERGH: That's hard.

00:46:08.190 --> 00:46:09.731
CARLA HALL: I know,
it's really hard.

00:46:09.731 --> 00:46:10.980
It's very hard.

00:46:10.980 --> 00:46:14.120
And it also depends
on where I am

00:46:14.120 --> 00:46:16.464
and what mood I'm
in, who I'm with.

00:46:16.464 --> 00:46:17.880
HILLARY BERGH:
What the season is.

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:19.620
CARLA HALL: Yeah, the season.

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:21.860
I do remember when
I got to New York,

00:46:21.860 --> 00:46:25.450
and it was probably
the first time

00:46:25.450 --> 00:46:26.830
that I went to ABC Kitchen.

00:46:30.540 --> 00:46:32.760
What's his restaurant?

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:34.500
Oh, my god.

00:46:34.500 --> 00:46:37.600
Not Daniel Boulud.

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:39.000
Have you got your glasses on?

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:39.944
You can look that up.

00:46:39.944 --> 00:46:40.890
AUDIENCE: George.

00:46:40.890 --> 00:46:41.890
CARLA HALL: John George.

00:46:41.890 --> 00:46:43.198
Thank you.

00:46:43.198 --> 00:46:43.698
What a girl.

00:46:43.698 --> 00:46:45.198
She didn't even
have the glasses on.

00:46:49.506 --> 00:46:50.940
The meal was amazing.

00:46:50.940 --> 00:46:53.150
The bread was so good.

00:46:53.150 --> 00:46:54.070
And it was pea season.

00:46:54.070 --> 00:46:55.000
And I love peas.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.790
And they had the
fava bean spread.

00:46:57.790 --> 00:47:00.800
And it was the fava
beans and the bread

00:47:00.800 --> 00:47:03.060
was just the perfect
amount of salt.

00:47:03.060 --> 00:47:03.760
And the spread.

00:47:03.760 --> 00:47:04.680
And the texture.

00:47:04.680 --> 00:47:05.680
And it was just so good.

00:47:05.680 --> 00:47:06.805
And I was like, oh, my god.

00:47:06.805 --> 00:47:09.718
This is the best I've ever had.

00:47:09.718 --> 00:47:12.130
And I've said that many times.

00:47:12.130 --> 00:47:14.350
But then I got to
dessert, and they

00:47:14.350 --> 00:47:18.090
had this like a
strawberry shortcake.

00:47:18.090 --> 00:47:20.060
And they had these
little tiny berries

00:47:20.060 --> 00:47:21.870
that was so perfectly sweet.

00:47:21.870 --> 00:47:26.990
And they had done an almost
like a-- not a coulis,

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:31.875
but a broth, or a syrup
of the strawberries.

00:47:31.875 --> 00:47:32.750
And they strained it.

00:47:32.750 --> 00:47:33.740
And it was so clear.

00:47:33.740 --> 00:47:37.865
And it had lime in it.

00:47:37.865 --> 00:47:41.140
And it was so perfectly
sweet and tangy.

00:47:41.140 --> 00:47:43.710
And then these little
berries, and the whipped cream

00:47:43.710 --> 00:47:45.360
was perfectly whipped.

00:47:45.360 --> 00:47:48.260
And this like angel
food cake, and--

00:47:51.920 --> 00:47:53.600
It was so good.

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:55.150
It was so, so good.

00:47:55.150 --> 00:47:58.910
And I love when somebody can
take ingredients and just

00:47:58.910 --> 00:47:59.580
let them sing.

00:47:59.580 --> 00:48:01.950
And it's not a lot of
fuss and a 1,000 people

00:48:01.950 --> 00:48:04.087
haven't touched it.

00:48:04.087 --> 00:48:05.170
And that was really great.

00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:08.460
Conversely, thinking
about that same dish,

00:48:08.460 --> 00:48:14.330
I went to a restaurant
and it was Jersey cream

00:48:14.330 --> 00:48:18.870
with Jersey blueberries-- it
was blueberry season-- and maple

00:48:18.870 --> 00:48:19.370
syrup.

00:48:19.370 --> 00:48:21.300
Doesn't that sound heavenly?

00:48:21.300 --> 00:48:29.590
Well, I got it, and the
cream was over-whipped

00:48:29.590 --> 00:48:31.930
just before it became butter.

00:48:31.930 --> 00:48:34.990
And then I move the spoon back--
so that of the first thing--

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:35.980
then I was like, oh--

00:48:35.980 --> 00:48:40.610
And I'm like, well, my maple
syrup wasn't even there.

00:48:40.610 --> 00:48:42.700
It was three ingredients
on the whole dish.

00:48:42.700 --> 00:48:44.170
One ingredient was over-whipped.

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:47.570
And then the other one, the
maple syrup, wasn't there.

00:48:47.570 --> 00:48:49.612
So then I said, well, my
maple syrup isn't there.

00:48:49.612 --> 00:48:51.111
And I didn't even
mention the cream.

00:48:51.111 --> 00:48:53.040
So they go back and
they put the maple syrup

00:48:53.040 --> 00:48:57.000
over the over-whipped cream,
which really curdled it up.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:00.921
It was like-- And
I was like, ugh.

00:49:00.921 --> 00:49:02.170
HILLARY BERGH: That's too bad.

00:49:02.170 --> 00:49:03.650
CARLA HALL: It's too bad, right?

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:04.480
It's too bad.

00:49:04.480 --> 00:49:06.600
So for me, the best
meal is like when

00:49:06.600 --> 00:49:09.160
you can celebrate a chef
by making something for you

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:10.290
and honoring the food.

00:49:10.290 --> 00:49:12.190
So it changes every time.

00:49:12.190 --> 00:49:14.200
When I went to your
place, it was so good

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:17.440
how you transported
me to the Philippines.

00:49:17.440 --> 00:49:19.649
It was amazing.

00:49:19.649 --> 00:49:21.440
Not that I'm interviewing
you, but have you

00:49:21.440 --> 00:49:22.398
been to a kamayan meal?

00:49:24.904 --> 00:49:29.230
So tell me, Hillary, I'm
glad you could come today.

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:30.940
Thank you all.

00:49:30.940 --> 00:49:32.590
HILLARY BERGH: Thank
you for having me.

00:49:32.590 --> 00:49:33.920
CARLA HALL: Yes, of course.

00:49:33.920 --> 00:49:35.604
Now you do such beautiful work.

00:49:35.604 --> 00:49:36.645
And you travel the globe.

00:49:36.645 --> 00:49:38.862
No.

00:49:38.862 --> 00:49:40.320
Have you ever have
to kamayan meal,

00:49:40.320 --> 00:49:43.680
like a Filipino feast, where
they do the kamayan meal where

00:49:43.680 --> 00:49:44.680
you eat with your hands?

00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:46.200
HILLARY BERGH: Yes, yes.

00:49:46.200 --> 00:49:47.950
I'm forgetting the
name of the restaurant,

00:49:47.950 --> 00:49:49.920
it's in Redwood City.

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:52.060
It's a sister
restaurant to Left Bank.

00:49:52.060 --> 00:49:54.300
I think it's the Brasserie.

00:49:54.300 --> 00:49:56.040
Anyway, the chef
there is Filipino.

00:49:56.040 --> 00:49:58.420
And last year, he did
this whole spread.

00:49:58.420 --> 00:50:00.710
And it was amazing.

00:50:00.710 --> 00:50:03.150
He has a calamondin
tree in his backyard.

00:50:03.150 --> 00:50:04.980
So he had fresh calamondins.

00:50:04.980 --> 00:50:06.614
And then he had
also preserved some.

00:50:06.614 --> 00:50:08.530
CARLA HALL: I just
discovered the calamondins,

00:50:08.530 --> 00:50:10.850
that little tart, sweet
orange that-- You guys,

00:50:10.850 --> 00:50:12.680
you have it good out here.

00:50:12.680 --> 00:50:14.290
You have it really good.

00:50:14.290 --> 00:50:16.810
Somebody sent me some from
Florida, it was so delicious.

00:50:16.810 --> 00:50:17.990
HILLARY BERGH: Yeah.

00:50:17.990 --> 00:50:18.920
The spread--

00:50:18.920 --> 00:50:19.410
CARLA HALL: Isn't it amazing?

00:50:19.410 --> 00:50:20.055
HILLARY BERGH: It was amazing.

00:50:20.055 --> 00:50:20.320
CARLA HALL: It's so good.

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:21.150
HILLARY BERGH: And
then, yeah, to get

00:50:21.150 --> 00:50:23.019
to play with the
food with your hands.

00:50:23.019 --> 00:50:23.685
CARLA HALL: Yes.

00:50:23.685 --> 00:50:23.960
Yes.

00:50:23.960 --> 00:50:25.530
HILLARY BERGH: I do love
eating with my hands.

00:50:25.530 --> 00:50:26.250
CARLA HALL: I do, too.

00:50:26.250 --> 00:50:27.060
But you know
there's an etiquette

00:50:27.060 --> 00:50:27.890
to eating with your hands.

00:50:27.890 --> 00:50:29.470
If you go above the
second knuckles,

00:50:29.470 --> 00:50:31.929
you're eating like an ape.

00:50:31.929 --> 00:50:33.720
HILLARY BERGH: There's
some delicacy to it.

00:50:33.720 --> 00:50:35.790
CARLA HALL: Yeah,
it's so fantastic.

00:50:35.790 --> 00:50:36.290
Yes?

00:50:36.290 --> 00:50:37.284
Sorry.

00:50:37.284 --> 00:50:39.450
AUDIENCE: Hi, I want to ask
you a question about one

00:50:39.450 --> 00:50:41.860
of the spices you have
in your very nice chart.

00:50:41.860 --> 00:50:42.974
It's saffron.

00:50:42.974 --> 00:50:43.640
CARLA HALL: Yes.

00:50:43.640 --> 00:50:45.348
AUDIENCE: So first,
is there a difference

00:50:45.348 --> 00:50:48.630
between the saffron that
is used for Persian food

00:50:48.630 --> 00:50:50.275
and the Spanish food?

00:50:50.275 --> 00:50:51.650
That would be the
first question.

00:50:51.650 --> 00:50:53.550
And the second one
is, how to use it.

00:50:53.550 --> 00:50:56.240
I been learning how
to make Spanish paella

00:50:56.240 --> 00:50:57.590
the last couple of weeks.

00:50:57.590 --> 00:50:59.620
And I've tried a
couple of times.

00:50:59.620 --> 00:51:01.250
But it's a mystery
how to use it.

00:51:01.250 --> 00:51:03.320
Lots of different
advice out there.

00:51:03.320 --> 00:51:07.161
And it makes it so unreliable,
unpredictable the result,

00:51:07.161 --> 00:51:07.660
right?

00:51:07.660 --> 00:51:11.085
So maybe I should go for a
saffron in powder version?

00:51:11.085 --> 00:51:13.062
Or I don't know-- no right?

00:51:13.062 --> 00:51:14.520
HILLARY BERGH:
Don't do the powder.

00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:16.609
AUDIENCE: I want to
find out a technique.

00:51:16.609 --> 00:51:18.275
CARLA HALL: You can
use a saffron powder

00:51:18.275 --> 00:51:19.020
if you wanted to.

